  "texts": [
    "Fig. 4 shows the transformation of information from source to destination via encryption and a secret key, followed by the reverse engineering process at the destination end using the same shared private key.",
    "Structure-Wise Lightweight Cryptographic AlgorithmsSymmetric keys and asymmetric keys are the two basic types of cryptographic algorithms (Fig. 5).",
    "Symmetric keys use a single key for both encryption and decryption, in contrast to asymmetric cyphers, which use two different keys for each operation [27].",
    "The only drawback of symmetric key encryption is the requirement to securely share the key between communicating parties without jeopardizing its confidentiality.",
    "This might be resolved by providing the key to a reliable third party in advance."
  ],
